00:13:42.810 --> 00:13:45.430
looking at. So the shapes, the texture, the edges.

239
00:13:45.950 --> 00:13:49.210
So it should describe in a very generic sense what is this image about.

240
00:13:49.610 --> 00:13:53.330
And then that description, these characteristics can be used for any kind of

241
00:13:53.370 --> 00:13:57.060
downstream task, for tumor detection, grading, but also outcome

242
00:13:57.130 --> 00:13:58.050
prediction, for instance.

243
00:14:01.710 --> 00:14:03.460
And I will not go into a lot of detail, but

244
00:14:04.330 --> 00:14:06.050
this is what we call self-supervised learning.

245
00:14:06.070 --> 00:14:08.050
It's the same thing that happened to ChatGPT.

246
00:14:08.270 --> 00:14:12.010
You all probably know that ChatGPT just took loads of texts from the

247
00:14:12.050 --> 00:14:15.830
internet, analyzed these texts without having a clear task in mind, and

248
00:14:15.890 --> 00:14:19.570
just found all kinds of, let's say, patterns in the text that it can

249
00:14:19.669 --> 00:14:23.390
use for downstream tasks, like generating new texts, understanding

250
00:14:23.470 --> 00:14:23.770
text.

251
00:14:24.570 --> 00:14:28.370
Now, the same happens here. We train our AI model on

252
00:14:28.390 --> 00:14:32.230
pathology data without a specific task. We give it a dummy task.

253
00:14:32.790 --> 00:14:36.530
But we give it a task that is very hard and that forces it to learn

254
00:14:36.610 --> 00:14:40.550
many generic aspects of the data without having a specific task

255
00:14:40.590 --> 00:14:44.370
in mind. If you're interested, you can look up the papers. It's very technical.

256
00:14:45.750 --> 00:14:49.350
And if you have done this, you have a very generic representation of your data.

257
00:14:49.450 --> 00:14:51.890
Then, for instance, what you can do is what is called few-shot learning.

258
00:14:52.570 --> 00:14:55.630
So now I have let's say different types of kidney cancer.

259
00:14:56.290 --> 00:14:59.370
What I can do is I can take a couple of examples of kidney cancer and see where

260
00:14:59.410 --> 00:15:01.270
they end up in this high dimensional space.

261
00:15:01.930 --> 00:15:05.490
And if I have three different types of kidney cancer, I take, in this case, three

262
00:15:05.530 --> 00:15:09.269
examples of each. So I have some points in the space that are here, some points

263
00:15:09.370 --> 00:15:13.010
that are here. Now, if I have a new cancer, what I can do is I can just

264
00:15:13.050 --> 00:15:16.650
calculate its place in this space and then see is it closer to this or closer to

265
00:15:16.690 --> 00:15:20.250
this point. So rather than having to take 10,000

266
00:15:21.170 --> 00:15:24.970
examples, as I showed you for prostate cancer grading, in this case, I can

267
00:15:25.030 --> 00:15:28.990
just take a couple of examples, and because I have such a rich embedding already,

268
00:15:29.050 --> 00:15:32.570
I have this self-supervised system, I can already do great things

269
00:15:33.090 --> 00:15:34.350
just with very little data points.

270
00:15:36.230 --> 00:15:38.690
Now, this is what was done in this study.

271
00:15:38.750 --> 00:15:42.480
So this is a study where they compared on one hand doing this, let's say,

272
00:15:43.030 --> 00:15:47.010
task specific learning with lots of cases, thousands of cases, and they compare it

273
00:15:47.050 --> 00:15:48.490
to the use of a foundation model.

274
00:15:49.470 --> 00:15:53.190
And what they found was, and please have a look at this graph.

275
00:15:53.390 --> 00:15:56.650
So here you can see on the X-axis, you see the amount of training data.

276
00:15:56.910 --> 00:16:00.690
So they have thousands of cases. On the Y-axis, you can see the quality of the

277
00:16:00.770 --> 00:16:02.590
AI that they built in this case.

278
00:16:03.510 --> 00:16:06.430
What you can see is the blue line is just the task specific learning.

279
00:16:06.510 --> 00:16:07.890
So this is what I showed you before.

280
00:16:07.930 --> 00:16:11.390
You train a model to really perform this one task as good as you can.

281
00:16:12.310 --> 00:16:16.110
And what you can see is this model, the blue line, is quite poor with

282
00:16:16.150 --> 00:16:20.130
little data, but it has a steep curve, and if you provide it

283
00:16:20.150 --> 00:16:23.910
with enough data, like 30% of the total here, you get a very high level of

284
00:16:23.950 --> 00:16:24.470
performance.

285
00:16:25.630 --> 00:16:28.370
The other two are based on foundation models.

286
00:16:28.540 --> 00:16:31.929
And what you can see is that with very little data, as little as 1% of your

287
00:16:32.770 --> 00:16:36.110
entire cohort, you can already have quite good performance.

288
00:16:37.230 --> 00:16:41.050
Still, what is also clear in this chart is that if you

289
00:16:41.110 --> 00:16:44.820
have enough data, the task specific model still outperforms the

290
00:16:44.870 --> 00:16:48.630
foundation model. So if you have a lot of data, then a foundation model

291
00:16:48.670 --> 00:16:52.230
may be less relevant because you can train it on a task

292
00:16:52.250 --> 00:16:53.470
specific manner.

293
00:16:54.790 --> 00:16:58.410
And the conclusion in this paper was that foundation models do great with little

294
00:16:58.450 --> 00:17:02.310
data. If you have enough data, a task specific model could do better.

295
00:17:03.230 --> 00:17:06.690
And what they found here was, especially for specific very rare pathologies, the

296
00:17:06.730 --> 00:17:08.171
foundation model didn't do so well.

297
00:17:09.381 --> 00:17:13.190
And one point that we may discuss later maybe is one of the

298
00:17:13.210 --> 00:17:16.421
drawbacks of foundation models is because they're huge models, they're pre-trained,

299
00:17:16.450 --> 00:17:20.330
and they're very large. In this case, the foundation model took up 35

300
00:17:20.370 --> 00:17:22.730
times more energy than a task specific model.

301
00:17:22.970 --> 00:17:25.911
So that's also a point to take into account, I guess.

302
00:17:27.310 --> 00:17:31.270
Now, one of the great things about foundation models is that we don't have

303
00:17:31.290 --> 00:17:33.610
to stick with just vision, as I showed you.

304
00:17:33.930 --> 00:17:35.390
I told you we have these representations,

305
00:17:36.250 --> 00:17:39.850
and what we can do is we can actually start to combine images with

306
00:17:40.070 --> 00:17:43.150
text. In this case, they used text captions. They used images.

307
00:17:44.050 --> 00:17:47.990
And what we can start doing now is we can build these self-supervised models, but

308
00:17:48.040 --> 00:17:49.750
then we can take the texts,

309
00:17:50.770 --> 00:17:54.430
combine the different embeddings, and use one embedding to make

310
00:17:54.630 --> 00:17:57.510
the other one, let's say, more precise, as I showed you.

311
00:17:57.670 --> 00:17:59.570
So you can use one as a context for the other.

312
00:18:00.450 --> 00:18:04.130
So what they do here is they built these embeddings, and then they start to combine

313
00:18:04.150 --> 00:18:07.470
these different modalities, and they refine their embeddings.

314
00:18:07.550 --> 00:18:09.290
They refine their system.

315
00:18:10.390 --> 00:18:14.210
And the great thing is now you can benefit not just from having the images, but

316
00:18:14.270 --> 00:18:17.140
having a combination of an image with, for instance, a pathology

317
00:18:17.210 --> 00:18:20.954
reportThis is still not task

318
00:18:20.964 --> 00:18:22.834
specific. It's still very generic.

319
00:18:22.894 --> 00:18:23.574
So it means that

320
00:18:24.414 --> 00:18:27.494
we don't need any kind of labels. We can train

321
00:18:27.834 --> 00:18:31.604
self-supervised this kind of a model with just pathology images and

322
00:18:32.094 --> 00:18:35.654
maybe associated reports. And so we can have the AI

323
00:18:35.834 --> 00:18:39.794
learn a lot of interesting features, interesting, let's

324
00:18:39.814 --> 00:18:43.694
say, relationships, by just feeding it with lots of images and

325
00:18:43.754 --> 00:18:45.354
lots of corresponding reports.

326
00:18:47.834 --> 00:18:47.994
And

327
00:18:49.054 --> 00:18:52.974
there are many of these models today. So this is one very recent, MuSi.

328
00:18:53.854 --> 00:18:57.174
In this case, you can see they did this self-supervised training with

329
00:18:57.434 --> 00:18:58.534
reports and with

330
00:18:59.574 --> 00:18:59.914
slides.

331
00:19:00.794 --> 00:19:04.174
And you can see actually that MuSi, in this case, it's not the largest model.

