00:20:05.094 --> 00:20:08.314
doable, but it's not performing great.

350
00:20:08.354 --> 00:20:10.654
If you do it only on a pathology report, it's a bit less.

351
00:20:10.754 --> 00:20:14.344
But if you combine the image and the report, then you can see that the combination

352
00:20:14.374 --> 00:20:17.494
of the two is much stronger, and you can get to quite decent performance even

353
00:20:18.314 --> 00:20:21.974
of 0.75, which is still not great, but you could see it's

354
00:20:22.334 --> 00:20:23.354
definitely better than it was.

355
00:20:25.334 --> 00:20:25.474
Now,

356
00:20:26.714 --> 00:20:27.094
one thing

357
00:20:27.934 --> 00:20:31.164
that is very important, and we may also touch upon that later in later

358
00:20:31.334 --> 00:20:31.963
presentations,

359
00:20:33.534 --> 00:20:36.194
foundation models are not always completely robust.

360
00:20:36.654 --> 00:20:37.054
And

361
00:20:38.154 --> 00:20:42.134
it means that what I set out to try and explain to you is

362
00:20:42.154 --> 00:20:44.834
a foundation model can work with less data.

363
00:20:45.654 --> 00:20:49.394
And because it was trained on a very large variety of data, you would like it to be

364
00:20:49.414 --> 00:20:51.394
more robust than task-specific models.

365
00:20:51.554 --> 00:20:55.434
So I showed you if we build a task-specific model and we try it out

366
00:20:55.514 --> 00:20:59.334
on new data, it might not perform as well as it did on the data it was

367
00:20:59.374 --> 00:21:03.354
trained on. And one of the great promises of foundation models, because it is

368
00:21:03.434 --> 00:21:06.994
trained on a very large diversity of data, is that it will

369
00:21:07.034 --> 00:21:10.974
generalize better because it has seen a lot of different training data.

370
00:21:13.154 --> 00:21:16.514
The variability in the training data actually is a very important topic,

371
00:21:17.234 --> 00:21:21.174
which has been shown. So we trained on much data, but the variability in

372
00:21:21.214 --> 00:21:24.674
this data basically decides a lot about how good

373
00:21:24.874 --> 00:21:26.254
the foundation model is.

374
00:21:27.154 --> 00:21:30.814
And what was done in this study is they defined some measure of

375
00:21:30.854 --> 00:21:34.764
foundation model robustness. So they define how robust is the foundation model.

376
00:21:36.154 --> 00:21:39.454
And what they found was that, well, that's not surprising.

377
00:21:39.574 --> 00:21:42.174
If you have more data that the model was trained on,

378
00:21:43.094 --> 00:21:47.054
robustness goes up. So you can see that the models that were trained on many data

379
00:21:47.634 --> 00:21:49.084
have also higher robustness.

380
00:21:50.074 --> 00:21:53.374
What you can also very nicely see here is the blue ones are just

