494
00:28:18.518 --> 00:28:22.398
So this is how typical deep learning pipeline look like before foundational

495
00:28:22.458 --> 00:28:25.148
models in the natural images. So you have your image as a first step.

496
00:28:25.198 --> 00:28:26.798
You're going to extract features from the images.

497
00:28:27.278 --> 00:28:29.078
You end up with the feature vector, as we just saw.

498
00:28:29.238 --> 00:28:32.858
And on the top of the feature vector, you're going to train your prediction model.

499
00:28:34.498 --> 00:28:37.898
And in the natural images, what we did before foundational model, it's so-called

500
00:28:37.998 --> 00:28:41.538
end-to-end learning. It means the model has to learn how to extract the features,

501
00:28:41.598 --> 00:28:45.317
how to make the predictions. It has to learn all these components together.

502
00:28:46.778 --> 00:28:47.898
And you saw that

503
00:28:48.758 --> 00:28:52.478
AI is very good with image analysis, and this model get fantastic

504
00:28:52.558 --> 00:28:56.518
performance, but they were trained on set of millions of images, so it's really

505
00:28:56.618 --> 00:28:59.938
large scale data. When we move to pathology,

506
00:29:00.658 --> 00:29:03.318
someone mentioned the multiple instance learning. This is how we handle the images.

507
00:29:03.398 --> 00:29:06.518
The images are huge. So we segment the tissue in the image.

508
00:29:06.558 --> 00:29:09.698
We divide the image into patches. Then we're going to extract features from the

509
00:29:09.738 --> 00:29:13.178
patches, and then we do some other operation, how to integrate information from the

510
00:29:13.198 --> 00:29:16.198
patches to build slide level representation, and we're going to do the predictions.

511
00:29:17.178 --> 00:29:20.458
Now, because we don't have millions of pathology images, we cannot really train

512
00:29:20.498 --> 00:29:23.098
this model end to end, and usually we don't do that.

513
00:29:23.538 --> 00:29:25.908
So the idea was to use transfer learning, and

514
00:29:26.758 --> 00:29:30.538
the observation is if you train your model on natural images, the early layers of

515
00:29:30.578 --> 00:29:34.438
this network's going to learn specific general image features like

516
00:29:34.518 --> 00:29:38.478
the color, shapes, intensities, and the later layer learn features that are

517
00:29:38.658 --> 00:29:41.178
relevant for the prediction of cats and dogs and other

518
00:29:42.118 --> 00:29:45.958
task. So what we do, we cut off the later layers,

519
00:29:46.038 --> 00:29:49.898
and we use the earlier layers to extract features, and we use it as a

520
00:29:50.278 --> 00:29:51.958
feature encoder for the histology images.

521
00:29:51.998 --> 00:29:55.718
So we leverage the information from the natural images to learn image features, and

522
00:29:55.758 --> 00:29:59.428
then we can extract features from the histopathology images, and we just

523
00:29:59.518 --> 00:30:03.298
modify. So this is how we were able to train the models on

524
00:30:03.318 --> 00:30:07.178
histology images that reach human level performance for a lot of task.

525
00:30:07.638 --> 00:30:10.558
But these models were trained on something of order of ten thousands of images.

526
00:30:10.658 --> 00:30:13.738
So for instance, Paige AI Prostate was trained on 60,000 images.

527
00:30:13.798 --> 00:30:16.118
It's the model that reached the first FDA approval.

528
00:30:16.818 --> 00:30:19.517
But we didn't need millions of images, but just ten thousands of

529
00:30:19.578 --> 00:30:22.986
images.One observation is this

