00:40:10.866 --> 00:40:14.156
out-of-distribution cases, it was able to generalize it, like interesting

711
00:40:14.226 --> 00:40:16.086
observation toward having generalized models.

712
00:40:16.526 --> 00:40:19.966
Not something to be used in practice, but interesting that we can generalize across

713
00:40:20.006 --> 00:40:20.526
diseases.

714
00:40:22.846 --> 00:40:24.306
One way-- oh, this is kind of important.

715
00:40:24.746 --> 00:40:28.566
So we were also looking at interpretability of the models having this

716
00:40:28.586 --> 00:40:32.546
attention heat map. So here this colorful map tell us what are the

717
00:40:32.566 --> 00:40:34.926
prognostic regions for each model prediction.

718
00:40:35.666 --> 00:40:39.326
And one take home message here is you can see the heat maps are not the same across

719
00:40:39.366 --> 00:40:41.886
the foundational models, even though we are doing the same task.

720
00:40:42.315 --> 00:40:46.146
So this is maybe something to be cautious about because people consider to

721
00:40:46.226 --> 00:40:49.886
use the high attention regions for biomarker

722
00:40:49.926 --> 00:40:53.906
exploration, but it depend on the choice of foundational model.

723
00:40:54.436 --> 00:40:57.945
So this is something we still maybe need to be careful about.

724
00:40:59.786 --> 00:41:03.586
The observation was, this is example of this out-of-distribution

725
00:41:03.686 --> 00:41:07.406
cases where the model was trained and some models like CONJ and Virchow, they were

726
00:41:07.466 --> 00:41:10.926
still able to find a tumor region, even though the model never saw this type of

727
00:41:10.946 --> 00:41:13.066
cancer. But it's interesting observation.

728
00:41:13.826 --> 00:41:15.596
But we have to be careful with interpretability.

729
00:41:18.006 --> 00:41:20.546
Another way to do interpretability is to look at the UMAPs.

730
00:41:20.826 --> 00:41:23.526
So here we take features extracted from the data,

731
00:41:24.746 --> 00:41:28.466
from the raw models, not trained for any specific task, and you can color it by the

732
00:41:28.506 --> 00:41:31.186
different cancer types. And we see that foundational models, they're doing very

733
00:41:31.266 --> 00:41:33.906
well separating different diseases in different subtypes.

734
00:41:34.546 --> 00:41:37.966
But now if you color it with respect to survival, you see it's very random.

735
00:41:38.006 --> 00:41:41.406
They are not better than ResNet. So this is what we saw the

736
00:41:41.646 --> 00:41:45.186
improvements on survival prediction wasn't so great with

737
00:41:45.226 --> 00:41:48.886
foundational model as we saw for the classification task, and it's because these

738
00:41:48.946 --> 00:41:51.246
feature don't carry additional prognostic information.

739
00:41:52.186 --> 00:41:53.446
So we decide to address it.

740
00:41:55.246 --> 00:41:59.145
We propose our own model. It's called Surfer because it's from California.

741
00:41:59.466 --> 00:42:02.706
Surfer is foundational model that is optimized for prognostic predictions,

742
00:42:02.966 --> 00:42:06.866
and it's a clip-and-sell model that's going to combine, again, images and text.

743
00:42:07.606 --> 00:42:11.526
But in contrast to previous models like CONJ, which combine histology image

744
00:42:11.586 --> 00:42:14.906
and text that describe the same image, so it's like pathology report,

745
00:42:15.526 --> 00:42:19.166
Surfer is going to combine images with the text, but the text contain

746
00:42:19.786 --> 00:42:22.446
patient outcomes. So we have information on survival treatment

747
00:42:22.486 --> 00:42:26.182
response.Also the idea is we want to inject this

748
00:42:26.202 --> 00:42:29.622
prognostic information in the text description so the model can use it to learn

749
00:42:29.662 --> 00:42:31.322
different prognostic features in the images.

750
00:42:32.122 --> 00:42:35.922
If you just use the CONV on its native way, it's a little bit tricky

751
00:42:35.962 --> 00:42:37.842
because it tries to push images

752
00:42:38.782 --> 00:42:42.202
with similar text together. But

753
00:42:42.722 --> 00:42:44.662
CLIP on its own doesn't have a notion of the time.

754
00:42:44.722 --> 00:42:48.002
It doesn't know that patient with survival of six months and eight months should be

755
00:42:48.042 --> 00:42:51.942
close in a feature space versus someone who has survival six months versus 20

756
00:42:51.982 --> 00:42:53.402
months should be more far in space.

757
00:42:53.962 --> 00:42:57.582
So we introduced this version of SoftCLIP, which is like a weighted version of

758
00:42:57.682 --> 00:43:01.582
CLIP, which introduces additional weightening based on the distance in the feature

759
00:43:01.682 --> 00:43:05.202
space. And it is to help the model to account for

760
00:43:05.262 --> 00:43:08.782
discontinuity of time. So patients who have similar survival now are going to be

761
00:43:08.902 --> 00:43:12.582
pushed closer together in a feature space, and those that have dissimilar survival

762
00:43:12.622 --> 00:43:15.902
will be pushed far away. And in this way, we can also now include patients with

763
00:43:15.942 --> 00:43:18.242
censored information because we just know when the

764
00:43:20.802 --> 00:43:24.742
patient was last observed, but we can still use it to push them apart from a

765
00:43:24.802 --> 00:43:26.382
patient that had very short survival.

766
00:43:27.142 --> 00:43:29.202
So this is the outline of the SURFER model.

767
00:43:30.162 --> 00:43:34.082
As a proof of concept, we trained SURFER using Titan as a

768
00:43:34.102 --> 00:43:37.622
backbone. So Titan is a vision language foundational model, which gives

769
00:43:37.722 --> 00:43:41.492
slide-level representation. So the SURFER uses Titan as a backbone,

770
00:43:42.222 --> 00:43:45.772
and it was trained on set of approximately 15,000 whole slide images from

771
00:43:45.782 --> 00:43:49.382
TCGA and from NIH-PLCO trial.

772
00:43:49.462 --> 00:43:53.122
And so if we look at the UMAPs between

773
00:43:53.382 --> 00:43:57.282
Titan versus SURFER colored with respect to the different cancer type, they are all

774
00:43:57.322 --> 00:44:00.702
similar. So SURFER is still able to separate different disease subtypes, so we

775
00:44:00.742 --> 00:44:02.122
didn't mess up the features too much.

776
00:44:02.842 --> 00:44:06.782
But now if we start looking at the features for a specific cancer, and we color

777
00:44:06.802 --> 00:44:08.222
them with respect to the survival.

778
00:44:08.862 --> 00:44:12.592
So on the top you can see we have bladder cancer and

779
00:44:12.662 --> 00:44:13.412
colorectal cancer,

780
00:44:14.302 --> 00:44:15.882
and at the top is performance with the SURFER.

781
00:44:15.942 --> 00:44:19.822
And you see there is no notion of the different risk groups for the patient

782
00:44:19.902 --> 00:44:23.102
with the same cancer type. But with the SURFER, because of this SoftCLIP

783
00:44:23.122 --> 00:44:26.782
pre-training, you can see a nice gradient of the different risk groups with

784
00:44:27.442 --> 00:44:31.202
respect to survival. So the model was able to find and stratify the patient with

785
00:44:31.222 --> 00:44:33.622
the same disease given the different risk groups.

786
00:44:33.641 --> 00:44:36.282
So it's like we are starting to learn some prognostic features.

787
00:44:36.732 --> 00:44:39.922
And then having better features, of course, you can translate it, and once you

788
00:44:39.962 --> 00:44:43.762
train the downstream models for survival prediction, it results in better

789
00:44:43.962 --> 00:44:47.342
survival prediction. So here in purple is Titan and dark is

790
00:44:47.382 --> 00:44:51.062
SURFER. So we could reach better survival performance.

791
00:44:52.182 --> 00:44:55.802
I don't claim that SURFER is the best solution.

792
00:44:55.862 --> 00:44:59.591
This is just the idea. Maybe we can benefit and improve the self-supervised

793
00:44:59.662 --> 00:45:03.352
learning and look at it slightly different to learn better prognostic features or

794
00:45:03.442 --> 00:45:05.922
features relevant for different outcomes.

795
00:45:07.302 --> 00:45:09.222
So this would be just to summarize.

796
00:45:09.282 --> 00:45:12.942
So what we saw, foundational models allow us to train more accurate and

797
00:45:12.962 --> 00:45:15.202
robust models while using less training data.

798
00:45:15.982 --> 00:45:19.472
We saw for developing foundational models, having more data doesn't

799
00:45:19.482 --> 00:45:20.282
necessarily mean

800
00:45:21.522 --> 00:45:25.222
better performance, but having better quality of the data, more patients, more

801
00:45:25.442 --> 00:45:27.442
diseases led to better representation.

802
00:45:28.052 --> 00:45:31.462
And we also saw that existing foundational models, they didn't perform so well for

803
00:45:31.502 --> 00:45:34.402
prognostic predictions. They are very good at separating patients with different

804
00:45:34.442 --> 00:45:38.102
disease type, but they don't stratify a patient with the same disease type with

805
00:45:38.182 --> 00:45:41.302
respect to the risk because there was no prognostic information included.

806
00:45:42.482 --> 00:45:45.482
And also one of these motivations, maybe we can move beyond standard

807
00:45:45.502 --> 00:45:49.442
self-supervised learning and try to inject additional information to learn

808
00:45:49.482 --> 00:45:52.642
better features maybe relevant for the prognostic.

809
00:45:52.922 --> 00:45:56.822
So again, I don't claim SURFER is the best direction, but it's suggestions maybe

810
00:45:56.842 --> 00:45:59.902
we can start looking at different ways to better leverage the data.

811
00:45:59.942 --> 00:46:03.502
Maybe it's not really self-supervised, but semi-self-supervised because we kind of

812
00:46:03.542 --> 00:46:04.492
inject the survival there.

813
00:46:05.702 --> 00:46:07.742
So maybe there is a space for other advances.

814
00:46:08.662 --> 00:46:12.182
And to move forward, of course, there is need for transparency.

815
00:46:12.222 --> 00:46:14.592
We have all these foundational models we don't know what they were trained on.

816
00:46:15.482 --> 00:46:18.502
They may be sensitive to different scanner types, different disease types, so it's

817
00:46:18.522 --> 00:46:20.282
like we would need more transparency.

818
00:46:20.782 --> 00:46:22.882
Having benchmarks is super helpful.

819
00:46:22.942 --> 00:46:26.342
It'll help us to understand what works for different data, what doesn't work,

820
00:46:26.842 --> 00:46:28.942
how to improve this model to move forward.

821
00:46:29.382 --> 00:46:33.042
Having private benchmark, like what Jacob and Gabriel did, is super helpful because

822
00:46:33.062 --> 00:46:36.822
it's independent testing, but also having public benchmark as our partners can be

823
00:46:36.862 --> 00:46:40.561
helpful because now if you develop own foundational models, you can just compare

824
00:46:40.602 --> 00:46:43.402
with the other models and see how they are doing.

825
00:46:43.442 --> 00:46:46.342
And the big question is how do we translate all of this to clinical practice?

