00:54:16.402 --> 00:54:18.742
plenary session at 8:00 a.m., which I'm looking forward to.

955
00:54:19.122 --> 00:54:20.902
But now let's speak about

956
00:54:21.882 --> 00:54:24.962
pathology foundation models, and the title that

957
00:54:26.182 --> 00:54:30.062
I gave my talk is not entirely correct because we've heard a lot

958
00:54:30.122 --> 00:54:33.952
about the technical basics and how we train and how

959
00:54:34.042 --> 00:54:37.452
we use foundation models in the two excellent previous

960
00:54:37.562 --> 00:54:41.286
talks. So now I want toSpeak to another topic

961
00:54:41.386 --> 00:54:44.686
which is: what can we use these models for?

962
00:54:44.806 --> 00:54:48.726
And this is relevant for cancer research, but also for clinical

963
00:54:48.826 --> 00:54:52.706
application. So let's get started. These are my disclosures.

964
00:54:54.506 --> 00:54:58.066
And I want to take this opportunity to take a

965
00:54:58.186 --> 00:55:02.166
step back to make very explicit the evolution

966
00:55:02.206 --> 00:55:06.066
of artificial intelligence in cancer research that we have witnessed

967
00:55:06.126 --> 00:55:09.726
over the last decades. It all started in the stone

968
00:55:09.826 --> 00:55:13.046
ages, right, in the 2000s or even before,

969
00:55:13.406 --> 00:55:16.646
with methods that we now call classical machine learning methods.

970
00:55:16.726 --> 00:55:20.526
If you have tabular data or you have features derived

971
00:55:20.586 --> 00:55:23.286
from image data or other more complex data, you can train

972
00:55:24.486 --> 00:55:25.346
these methods

973
00:55:26.306 --> 00:55:29.166
for classification, segmentation, prediction tasks.

974
00:55:29.546 --> 00:55:33.486
They work pretty well. They still have their role to play today,

975
00:55:33.906 --> 00:55:37.646
but they don't work for the real-world messy, complex

976
00:55:37.786 --> 00:55:40.806
image data that we encounter in cancer research.

977
00:55:41.026 --> 00:55:44.086
These are methods that you can basically use in Microsoft Excel or on your

978
00:55:45.026 --> 00:55:48.786
calculator, and they're still very important, but we have to have

979
00:55:48.846 --> 00:55:51.646
more complex methods to deal with more complex data.

980
00:55:52.256 --> 00:55:55.966
And these methods came along in the form of deep

981
00:55:56.046 --> 00:55:59.546
learning in the 2010s, specifically in 2012, when the first

982
00:55:59.626 --> 00:56:02.886
convolutional neural networks had their success stories.

983
00:56:03.256 --> 00:56:07.006
And this enabled us, for the first time, to analyze

984
00:56:07.046 --> 00:56:10.046
pathology slides really robustly.

985
00:56:10.426 --> 00:56:11.026
And

986
00:56:12.306 --> 00:56:15.626
deep learning methods, of course, deep neural networks, you need a lot of data to

987
00:56:15.666 --> 00:56:19.446
train them, and then you can solve any pathology image analysis problem that you're

988
00:56:19.486 --> 00:56:23.406
interested in. But this data abundance was the main

989
00:56:23.506 --> 00:56:26.426
practical limitation that held the field back.

990
00:56:26.526 --> 00:56:30.006
And I think the technology of foundation models

991
00:56:30.166 --> 00:56:33.606
fundamentally changed this because with the foundation model, as we have heard

992
00:56:33.746 --> 00:56:36.866
beautifully articulated in the previous talks, you

993
00:56:37.346 --> 00:56:39.146
train one big model

994
00:56:40.126 --> 00:56:43.506
one time, and then you can use it many times for many downstream tasks.

995
00:56:43.686 --> 00:56:47.326
Sure, you need a lot of images. Sure, you need a lot of

996
00:56:47.466 --> 00:56:51.306
energy to train this model. But once you have it, it's frozen

997
00:56:51.406 --> 00:56:53.266
forever. It's there. You can use it forever.

998
00:56:53.556 --> 00:56:57.546
And you don't need so much downstream data every time you want to solve a

999
00:56:57.586 --> 00:57:01.566
new task in a new cancer type. And that is the beauty of foundation models, and

1000
00:57:01.626 --> 00:57:03.806
that's why they have been so transformative in pathology

1001
00:57:03.926 --> 00:57:07.246
image analysis in cancer research.

1002
00:57:07.546 --> 00:57:11.406
Another type of foundation models is large language models,

1003
00:57:11.506 --> 00:57:15.466
right? Everybody knows them. Everybody uses ChatGPT, Claude, or

1004
00:57:15.526 --> 00:57:19.396
all these models. They're also foundation models that have been trained with

1005
00:57:19.396 --> 00:57:21.426
self-supervised learning on language.

1006
00:57:21.435 --> 00:57:24.166
And this happened more or less in parallel, right?

1007
00:57:24.206 --> 00:57:27.036
And now these models are also becoming very useful.

1008
00:57:27.506 --> 00:57:31.486
One reason why they're becoming useful in cancer research is because you can

1009
00:57:31.646 --> 00:57:35.606
build AI agents around them, and I will show you some examples for

1010
00:57:35.686 --> 00:57:39.526
that. But before we go into the future-looking things, let

1011
00:57:39.586 --> 00:57:43.226
me focus again on the foundation models, on the image analysis, and what we can do

1012
00:57:43.286 --> 00:57:43.586
with them.

1013
00:57:45.026 --> 00:57:48.486
In terms of applications, what do we want to use image

1014
00:57:48.506 --> 00:57:51.646
analysis in cancer research and oncology for?

1015
00:57:52.006 --> 00:57:55.556
Well, for many years, the answer was object detection,

1016
00:57:55.906 --> 00:57:59.506
cancer detection, right? In colonoscopy videos, we want to

1017
00:57:59.546 --> 00:58:02.106
detect polyps. In mammography

1018
00:58:03.626 --> 00:58:06.126
x-ray images, we want to detect breast cancer.

1019
00:58:06.506 --> 00:58:09.726
In pathology slides, we want to detect prostate cancer.

1020
00:58:10.046 --> 00:58:13.826
So we want to detect cancer, and this works so well that

1021
00:58:13.966 --> 00:58:17.906
basically in all these examples that I just gave you, these models have reached

1022
00:58:17.946 --> 00:58:21.546
human expert performance. You can train a model that's as good as any human

1023
00:58:21.606 --> 00:58:25.166
expert. It's consistent. It has been shown repeatedly in large prospective

1024
00:58:25.206 --> 00:58:27.685
randomized trials to hundreds of thousands of people.

1025
00:58:28.206 --> 00:58:31.186
This technology is robust. The problem is solved, right?

1026
00:58:31.246 --> 00:58:35.096
If you have enough data and one specific question for tumor detection

1027
00:58:35.466 --> 00:58:39.046
problem, problem solved. Of course, it does not solve all of our problems in the

1028
00:58:39.086 --> 00:58:40.806
real world because there's more than

1029
00:58:41.606 --> 00:58:45.046
just a small number of tumor types and

1030
00:58:45.646 --> 00:58:47.656
there's many challenges. I will speak to that later.

1031
00:58:47.736 --> 00:58:49.406
But from a technical perspective, these

1032
00:58:50.446 --> 00:58:53.546
things are now very well manageable.

1033
00:58:54.586 --> 00:58:58.465
That's why we can also look at more complicated tasks, and

1034
00:58:58.526 --> 00:59:02.166
that's what our research group did for many years now.

1035
00:59:02.226 --> 00:59:06.086
This is an ancient paper from our group where for the first time

1036
00:59:06.206 --> 00:59:10.026
we looked at different questions in pathology

1037
00:59:10.066 --> 00:59:13.286
image analysis. Can we predict molecular

1038
00:59:13.366 --> 00:59:16.766
alterations directly from pathology slides?

1039
00:59:16.826 --> 00:59:20.746
So this is a more challenging problem than making a diagnosis of

1040
00:59:20.786 --> 00:59:24.716
cancer because you cannot even be sure that the information

1041
00:59:24.786 --> 00:59:28.746
is represented in the image. But what we saw in this study

1042
00:59:28.766 --> 00:59:32.386
and in what others have shown in hundreds of other studies is

1043
00:59:32.426 --> 00:59:36.186
that many molecular alterations leave a

1044
00:59:36.246 --> 00:59:39.906
unique footprint in the tumor morphology, that you can

1045
00:59:40.046 --> 00:59:42.246
infer them just by looking at the morphology.

1046
00:59:42.706 --> 00:59:46.666
And this is not perfect, but it's good enough to be useful in many cases,

1047
00:59:46.746 --> 00:59:48.586
for example, for pre-screening.

1048
00:59:50.686 --> 00:59:54.566
Another example, a lot of work has been done with-- What I showed you here

1049
00:59:54.626 --> 00:59:56.506
was microsatellite instability.

1050
00:59:56.566 --> 00:59:59.446
Another example is homologous recombination deficiency.

1051
00:59:59.926 --> 01:00:03.766
These are gene signatures that basically mess

1052
01:00:03.866 --> 01:00:06.306
up with the tumor genome at many

1053
01:00:07.406 --> 01:00:11.376
levels and therefore also leave a footprint in the tumor morphology,

1054
01:00:11.486 --> 01:00:14.186
which you can infer with pathology image analysis.

1055
01:00:14.866 --> 01:00:17.406
This even goes for other more complex

1056
01:00:18.386 --> 01:00:21.346
genetic or molecular changes in the tumor.

1057
01:00:21.426 --> 01:00:22.226
For example,

1058
01:00:23.606 --> 01:00:27.286
transcriptomic signatures that are correlated to

1059
01:00:27.346 --> 01:00:30.786
patient outcomes. We know, for example, in breast cancer, there is

1060
01:00:30.826 --> 01:00:33.966
established risk scores such as Oncotype DX, MammaPrint,

1061
01:00:34.626 --> 01:00:34.866
that

1062
01:00:36.586 --> 01:00:36.766
are

1063
01:00:37.586 --> 01:00:40.266
related to clinical outcomes of these patients, but

1064
01:00:41.506 --> 01:00:44.586
you need to measure basically the tumor transcriptome.

1065
01:00:44.946 --> 01:00:48.886
Well, here in this work and in many other studies that came out

1066
01:00:49.266 --> 01:00:52.346
in this fieldAnd it was shown that

1067
01:00:53.506 --> 01:00:57.505
just the tumor morphology is enough to infer

1068
01:00:57.866 --> 01:00:59.606
these signatures from morphology.

1069
01:00:59.666 --> 01:01:03.006
Sure, it's not perfect, but it's good enough to be useful in many cases.

1070
01:01:03.046 --> 01:01:06.806
This is joint work by Kevin Boom and Omar Elnahas who are here in the audience.

1071
01:01:06.826 --> 01:01:09.296
So if you have any questions, you can approach them

1072
01:01:10.126 --> 01:01:10.616
directly.

1073
01:01:12.106 --> 01:01:14.826
What this also enables us to do is to

1074
01:01:15.606 --> 01:01:17.586
undertake explainability

1075
01:01:18.766 --> 01:01:22.746
analysis in these tumors and try to understand which cellular

1076
01:01:22.886 --> 01:01:26.486
patterns are related to these molecular changes.

1077
01:01:26.566 --> 01:01:30.486
And for example, here you can see we can even train generative models

1078
01:01:30.546 --> 01:01:33.866
to generate low-risk or high-risk

1079
01:01:34.706 --> 01:01:38.626
image areas. And you can see that we can then look at these images and

1080
01:01:39.526 --> 01:01:41.886
draw conclusions from it. For example, one

1081
01:01:42.866 --> 01:01:46.486
of these classes has maybe more stroma or less stroma, or more

1082
01:01:46.646 --> 01:01:50.506
vessels or more lymphocytes or more myeloid cells, et cetera.

1083
01:01:50.586 --> 01:01:54.566
So we can inform all of these biological hypothesis just

1084
01:01:54.606 --> 01:01:57.266
by training these models on pathology slides.

1085
01:01:59.126 --> 01:02:02.506
All of this has been enabled and facilitated

1086
01:02:03.406 --> 01:02:06.726
massively by foundation models. In the past, when in

1087
01:02:06.846 --> 01:02:10.746
2019 we did the first studies, we had to train each model from scratch

1088
01:02:10.756 --> 01:02:14.406
to predict these properties of tumors from images.

1089
01:02:14.526 --> 01:02:18.286
Now it's much easier. We can start at a much higher level.

1090
01:02:18.366 --> 01:02:20.826
We just start with a foundation model, right?

1091
01:02:20.866 --> 01:02:21.326
And then we

1092
01:02:22.646 --> 01:02:25.806
train another model on top of it. So you need much less data.

1093
01:02:25.846 --> 01:02:29.546
It's much better generalizable, it's much faster. You need much less compute.

1094
01:02:29.586 --> 01:02:33.546
It's just now becoming very easy to do this.

1095
01:02:33.856 --> 01:02:35.746
And this is a figure that I adapted from

1096
01:02:36.846 --> 01:02:38.966
Jana's paper without asking. Sorry, Jana.

1097
01:02:39.006 --> 01:02:41.826
I hope that's okay because I think it

1098
01:02:42.306 --> 01:02:46.266
visualizes the concepts again that I want to repeat here about foundation models.

1099
01:02:46.326 --> 01:02:49.246
Which concepts are relevant here? You have data.

1100
01:02:49.286 --> 01:02:53.026
You train a model to compress the data. What you get is an embedding.

1101
01:02:53.296 --> 01:02:56.686
It's just a list of numbers, and with this list of numbers, it's much easier to

1102
01:02:56.746 --> 01:03:00.505
work with this than with an original image, which has many millions

1103
01:03:02.406 --> 01:03:06.146
of pixels. These foundation models can be easily

1104
01:03:06.326 --> 01:03:07.366
generalized to

1105
01:03:08.166 --> 01:03:10.506
go from unimodal to multimodal foundation models.

1106
01:03:10.546 --> 01:03:12.926
That's another advantage, right?

1107
01:03:12.966 --> 01:03:16.786
And then if you have multimodal foundation models, you have one representation

1108
01:03:16.846 --> 01:03:19.566
for multiple data modalities, which can be very powerful.

1109
01:03:19.926 --> 01:03:23.806
Powerful for what? For many downstream tasks, and I put some of

1110
01:03:23.846 --> 01:03:26.826
these tasks here, and we've seen them in the previous talks.

1111
01:03:27.266 --> 01:03:30.806
What you can easily do with these foundation model embeddings is

1112
01:03:31.806 --> 01:03:34.126
solve the example applications that I've shown you before.

1113
01:03:34.466 --> 01:03:38.326
Prediction, prognostication, inference of molecular

1114
01:03:38.366 --> 01:03:42.166
alterations from morphology. But also you can retrieve

1115
01:03:42.246 --> 01:03:46.186
similar patients. All these patients live in a high-dimensional

1116
01:03:46.286 --> 01:03:48.526
space that's defined by your foundation model

1117
01:03:49.846 --> 01:03:53.446
feature space. And then you can retrieve the closest patients,

1118
01:03:53.586 --> 01:03:57.446
patients like me, right? You can also retrieve closest patients for

1119
01:03:57.466 --> 01:03:58.946
potential clinical trial matching.

1120
01:03:59.026 --> 01:04:02.796
You can retrieve patients or work in this embedding

1121
01:04:02.846 --> 01:04:05.326
space to generate virtual trial arms.

1122
01:04:05.726 --> 01:04:09.706
So there's a lot of downstream tasks that go beyond these predictive

1123
01:04:09.766 --> 01:04:13.586
tasks that I showed you. So foundation models are really cool

1124
01:04:13.806 --> 01:04:16.886
and everybody's using them, and there's no way to not use them when you're

1125
01:04:17.706 --> 01:04:19.446
working with pathology images

1126
01:04:20.626 --> 01:04:22.846
nowadays. We've benchmarked them in our team.

1127
01:04:22.886 --> 01:04:23.986
This study has been shown

1128
01:04:25.506 --> 01:04:26.486
much more elegantly by

1129
01:04:27.426 --> 01:04:31.276
the previous speakers. And I think benchmarking is something that's very

1130
01:04:31.326 --> 01:04:33.616
important, that's generally underappreciated.

1131
01:04:34.066 --> 01:04:37.706
As we have more and more models out there, benchmarking on

1132
01:04:37.846 --> 01:04:38.746
private data

1133
01:04:39.566 --> 01:04:39.786
with

1134
01:04:40.726 --> 01:04:43.986
reasonable use case, with relevant use cases becomes even

1135
01:04:44.086 --> 01:04:45.046
more

1136
01:04:46.286 --> 01:04:46.886
important.

1137
01:04:48.346 --> 01:04:51.946
Now, there is a paradox. This technology is extremely

1138
01:04:52.066 --> 01:04:52.566
powerful.

1139
01:04:53.606 --> 01:04:56.166
It's not so difficult to train it. We know that it can

1140
01:04:57.246 --> 01:05:00.906
solve many questions that are clinically interesting,

1141
01:05:00.926 --> 01:05:04.406
but at the same time, almost nobody's using it, right?

1142
01:05:04.466 --> 01:05:08.086
Let's be honest. We've heard less than 10% of pathology slides in the

1143
01:05:08.146 --> 01:05:11.126
US are read digitally. I think it's even less.

1144
01:05:11.205 --> 01:05:14.286
I think it's even less than 5% in Europe.

1145
01:05:14.706 --> 01:05:18.206
It's very good in some countries, but very bad in other countries.

1146
01:05:18.626 --> 01:05:21.906
Overall, of course, most pathology slides are not

1147
01:05:21.926 --> 01:05:25.866
digital, and therefore these methods cannot be used in

1148
01:05:25.906 --> 01:05:29.846
clinical routine. And I think it's these barriers here that's just from

1149
01:05:29.886 --> 01:05:33.106
an article that we wrote a while ago about barriers to implementation, which I

1150
01:05:33.126 --> 01:05:34.446
think is still valid.

1151
01:05:36.026 --> 01:05:39.846
Now we are not facing so much of a scientific problem anymore.

1152
01:05:39.886 --> 01:05:41.906
We're just facing an implementation problem.

1153
01:05:41.926 --> 01:05:45.466
And sometimes for scientists tackling these boring

1154
01:05:45.526 --> 01:05:49.306
implementation problems, it's not very appealing, but I think it's what we

1155
01:05:49.406 --> 01:05:53.046
have to do to really reap the benefits of this

1156
01:05:53.056 --> 01:05:54.246
technology in

1157
01:05:55.126 --> 01:05:56.406
patient care ultimately,

1158
01:05:57.386 --> 01:06:00.946
and in cancer research. And I hope we can have some

1159
01:06:01.006 --> 01:06:02.136
discussions about this

1160
01:06:03.486 --> 01:06:06.466
in the panel discussion. We are seeing some

1161
01:06:06.546 --> 01:06:10.506
encouraging signals, though. This is a study

1162
01:06:10.926 --> 01:06:14.686
led by Gabriele Campanella from New York, where

1163
01:06:14.706 --> 01:06:18.646
last year they published a beautiful study, and many

1164
01:06:18.706 --> 01:06:22.626
people who are here in the room were involved with this study, where they

1165
01:06:22.726 --> 01:06:26.636
ran an actual trial, a prospective evaluation,

1166
01:06:26.766 --> 01:06:30.336
to use this technology for screening of molecular

1167
01:06:30.386 --> 01:06:32.336
alterations from pathology slides.

1168
01:06:32.366 --> 01:06:36.066
In this case, predicting EGFR mutations in lung

1169
01:06:36.146 --> 01:06:38.946
cancer just based on the pathology slides.

1170
01:06:39.256 --> 01:06:42.465
And it worked pretty well even in this prospective study.

1171
01:06:42.486 --> 01:06:42.686
And

1172
01:06:43.546 --> 01:06:47.506
I recommend you to read this paper. I think it's very elegant.

1173
01:06:47.536 --> 01:06:51.466
The study design is very elegant, and they can make very

1174
01:06:51.626 --> 01:06:53.606
good statements, very strong statements here.

1175
01:06:54.486 --> 01:06:57.626
It reduced the number of rapid molecular tests by

1176
01:06:57.946 --> 01:07:01.806
43% while maintaining the current clinical performance.

1177
01:07:01.866 --> 01:07:04.606
So it's not a perfect test, but it can be useful,

1178
01:07:05.406 --> 01:07:09.206
especially in settings that are not as well-resourced as

1179
01:07:10.366 --> 01:07:11.946
here, Memorial Sloan,

1180
01:07:12.946 --> 01:07:16.910
where this study was conducted.Now,

1181
01:07:17.890 --> 01:07:21.350
why is this technology not being used widely?

1182
01:07:21.830 --> 01:07:25.570
Well, I spoke to the implementation hurdles, digitalization.

1183
01:07:25.960 --> 01:07:28.230
Another problem is that

1184
01:07:29.050 --> 01:07:32.050
even if all the infrastructure is there, the

